# Complete Implementation

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>
#include <cstring>

void write_data_to_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, uint32_t value, const void* data, std::size_t length) {
    // Write the integer value
    buffer.write(&value, sizeof(value));
    // Write the byte array
    buffer.write(data, length);
}

void read_data_from_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, uint32_t& value, void* data, std::size_t length) {
    // Read the integer value
    buffer.read(&value, sizeof(value));
    // Read the byte array
    buffer.read(data, length);
}

struct BufferInfo {
    std::size_t size;
    std::size_t free_space;
};

BufferInfo get_buffer_info(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer) {
    BufferInfo info;
    // Get current buffer size
    info.size = buffer.size();
    // Free space represents how much data is available to read
    // In PMC buffers, this is typically the same as size (readable data)
    info.free_space = buffer.size();
    return info;
}
```

## Explanation:

1. **`write_data_to_buffer`**: 
   - Uses `buffer.write()` to write the `uint32_t` value (4 bytes) followed by the byte array
   - The `write()` method takes a pointer to source data and length

2. **`read_data_from_buffer`**: 
   - Uses `buffer.read()` to read the `uint32_t` value followed by the byte array
   - The `read()` method takes a pointer to destination and length, reading and advancing the read position

3. **`get_buffer_info`**: 
   - Uses `buffer.size()` to get the current buffer size
   - Sets `free_space` to the current size, representing available readable data in the PMC buffer context

